A more precise understanding of the sorption mechanism of AO7 dye, AB14 dye, and Cr6+ ions to AC5-600 is essential. This depends on the textural and surface properties of the AC5-600 adsorbent and how the sorbate diffuses towards the adsorbent, with a blend of chemisorption and physisorption driving the sorption process of AO7 and AB14 dye. As observed from the IR analysis, both anionic dye molecules were sorbed to the AC5-600 owing to the physical electrostatic interaction/attraction between H+ FGs such as alkane on the surface of the synthesized AC5-600 and the -vely charged sulfonate anion dye molecules through ion-exchange. These groups can draw species with opposite charges and repel those with similar charges. Furthermore, the removal of these dyes consists of hydrogen bonding and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
